{{Expand German|Grotta-Pelos-Kultur|date=February 2016}}

[[Image:Violin-shaped female cycladic figurines.jpg|thumb|right|Violin-shaped Grotta-Pelos figurines.]]
[[Image:Getty Villa - lidded container with a herringbone pattern - inv. 91.AE.30.JPG|thumb|right|Lidded container with herringbone pattern.]]
The '''Grotta-Pelos culture''' ({{lang-el|Γρόττα-Πηλός}}) refers to a "cultural" dating system used for part of the early [[Bronze Age]] in [[Greece]].<ref name="Cline">Eric H. Cline (ed.), ''The Oxford Handbook of the Bronze Age Aegean'', {{ISBN|9780199873609}}, Jan. 2012.</ref> Specifically, it is the period that marks the beginning of the so-called [[Cycladic culture]] and spans the [[Neolithic]] period in the late [[4th millennium BC]] (ca. 3300 BC), continuing in the Bronze Age to about 2700 BC.
The term was coined by [[Colin Renfrew, Baron Renfrew of Kaimsthorn|Colin Renfrew]], who named it after the sites of Grotta and Pelos on the [[Cyclades|Cycladic]] islands of [[Naxos]] and [[Milos]], respectively. Other archaeologists prefer a [[Chronological dating|"chronological" dating]] system and refer to this period as the '''Early Cycladic I (ECI)'''.

