The '''Hirvepark meeting''' was held in [[Estonian Soviet Socialist Republic|Estonia]] on 23 August 1987, the anniversary of the [[Nazi-Soviet Pact]]. It was attended by 2,000 to 5,000 people, and was one of the first organized public demonstrations against the [[Estonian Communist Party]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Estonia: identity and independence |last= Subrenat |first=Jean-Jacques |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2004 |publisher=Rodopi |location= |isbn=978-0-8108-4904-4 |page=228 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kBZlHdp7tdcC&pg=RA1-PA228&dq=%22Hirvepark+meeting%22 |accessdate=}}</ref> It sparked a wave of anti-Soviet activity and mass protests in support of independence.<ref>{{cite book |title=Historical dictionary of Estonia |last=Miljan |first=Toivo |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2004 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |location= |isbn=978-0-8108-4904-4 |page=399 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xeXwMDZbTBoC&pg=PA399&dq=%22Hirvepark+meeting%22 |accessdate=}}</ref>

