{{Italic title}} {{Taxobox | name = ''Salpa fusiformis'' | image = Salpa fusiformis 001.png | image_caption = 1804 illustration by [[Georges Cuvier]] of ''Salpa fusiformis'' anatomy: '''A''' chain form; '''B''' solitary form; '''1-9''' : muscle bands; '''em''' - embryo; '''m''' - mantle; '''visc''' - visceral mass or nucleus | regnum = [[Animal]]ia | phylum = [[Chordata]] | subphylum = [[Tunicate|Tunicata]] | classis = [[Thaliacea]] | ordo = [[Salpida]] | familia = [[Salpidae]] | genus = ''[[Salpa (salp)|Salpa]]'' | species = '''''S. fusiformis''''' | binomial = ''Salpa fusiformis'' | binomial_authority = [[Georges Cuvier|Cuvier]], 1804 | synonyms_ref=<ref name="worms">{{cite WoRMS|author= L. Madin|year=2014|id=137272 |title=''Salpa fusiformis'' Cuvier, 1804 |accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> | synonyms= *''Biphora depressa''<small> Sars, 1829 </small> *''Biphora tricuspidata''<small> Sars, 1829 </small> *''Salpa clostra''<small> Milne-Edwards, 1828 </small> *''Salpa coerulea''<small> Quoy & Gaimard, 1834 </small> *''Salpa emarginata''<small> Quoy & Gaimard, 1824 </small> *''Salpa moniliformis''<small> Macculloch, 1819 </small> *''Salpa pyramidalis''<small> Lesson, 1832 </small> *''Salpa runcinata''<small> Chamisso, 1819 </small> *''Salpa tricuspidata''<small> Sars, 1829 </small> }}
'''''Salpa fusiformis''''', sometimes known as the '''common salp''',<ref name="worms"/> is the most widespread [[species]] of [[salp]]. They have a [[cosmopolitan distribution]], and can be found at depths of {{convert|0|to|800|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name="mdb"/> They exhibit [[diel vertical migration]], moving closer to the surface at night.<ref name="jz">{{cite web|url=http://jellieszone.com/salpa.htm|title=''Salpa fusiformis'' Cuvier, 1804|publisher=JelliesZone|accessdate=21 January 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528174714/http://jellieszone.com/salpa.htm|archivedate=28 May 2014|df=}}</ref><ref name="scr">{{cite web|url=https://scripps.ucsd.edu/zooplanktonguide/species/salpa-fusiformis|title=''Salpa fusiformis''|work=Zooplankton of the San Diego Region|publisher=Scripps Institution of Oceanography|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> They can occur in very dense swarms, as solitary [[zooid]]s or as colonies. Solitary zooids usually measure {{convert|22|to|52|mm|in|abbr=on}} in length. They are barrel-shaped and elongated, with a rounded front and a flat rear. Aggregate zooids are {{convert|7|to|52|mm|in|abbr=on}} in length individually (excluding projections). They are usually barrel or spindle-shaped.<ref name="mdb">{{cite web|url=http://species-identification.org/species.php?species_group=zmns&id=582|title=''Salpa fusiformis''|work=Zooplankton and Micronekton of the North Sea |author=Matthijs van Couwelaar|date=2003|publisher=Marine Species Identification Portal|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref>
